  "layman_summary": {
    "value": "A federal safety agency called the CPSC looked at the dangers of lead paint and decided to ban paints and surface coatings that contain more than 0.06 percent lead. This rule would also ban toys, children's furniture, and other kids' products covered with those high-lead coatings. The main reason is to protect children, who can get seriously sick from swallowing chips or flakes of lead paint found on walls, toys, and furniture. The ban is expected to lower the risk of lead poisoning in kids. On the downside, paint companies would need to change their formulas and test their products regularly, costing the industry roughly $5–8 million per year, with the biggest financial hit falling on makers of specialty coatings like auto and industrial paints.",
